{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657800","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657800"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:35:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:35:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20651"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20651","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20651"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0,0.05,0.77,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13527"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95008"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13527","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13527"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20651"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77982"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11585"},{"type":"tags","id":"11782"},{"type":"tags","id":"12538"},{"type":"tags","id":"12539"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32304"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32305"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95008","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95008"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESkin wounds heal through a complex process that involves inflammation, cell proliferation, and tissue remodelling. The specific healing pattern depends on the nature and extent of the injury.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a characteristic feature of wound healing by second intention compared to first intention?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decreased inflammatory response","Complete regeneration of dermal appendages","Reduced risk of scar formation","Greater formation of granulation tissue","Faster recovery of tensile strength"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHealing by second intention occurs in wounds with significant tissue loss, requiring \u003Cstrong\u003Egreater formation of granulation tissue\u003C/strong\u003E to fill the defect. This results in more extensive scarring compared to healing by first intention, where wound edges are closely approximated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased inflammatory response\u003C/strong\u003E - Second intention healing actually involves a more pronounced inflammatory response due to larger amounts of debris and damaged tissue requiring removal\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete regeneration of dermal appendages\u003C/strong\u003E - Neither healing type allows regeneration of destroyed skin appendages like hair follicles or sweat glands\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced risk of scar formation\u003C/strong\u003E - Second intention healing produces more prominent scarring due to increased granulation tissue formation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFaster recovery of tensile strength\u003C/strong\u003E - Both healing types achieve similar final strength (70-80% of original) over the same timeframe\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESecond intention healing is characterised by:\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EFormation of abundant granulation tissue to fill the tissue defect\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EWound contraction mediated by myofibroblasts\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EMore prominent scarring\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EMore intense inflammatory response\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Wound healing by first intention occurs in clean, approximated wounds with minimal tissue loss, while healing by second intention occurs in wounds with large tissue defects.","Healing by second intention requires more granulation tissue formation and results in more prominent scarring compared to first intention healing.","Wound contraction by myofibroblasts is a key feature of second intention healing that reduces wound size.","Final wound strength reaches approximately 70-80% of normal tissue strength regardless of healing type."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 3, Inflammation and Repair; p. 108-110"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77982"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20651"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77982","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/77982"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-26T20:56:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-26T20:57:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13527"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95008"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11585"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Inflammation and repair","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":2,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T15:14:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T15:14:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11782","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11782"},"attribute